</section>
</div>

<div class="lang-en">
<section id="traditions">
  <h2>Traditional Customs</h2>
  <p>Qingming customs have been practised for centuries with remarkable consistency. The core traditions are:</p>
  <p><strong>Tomb sweeping (<span class="chinese-char">掃墓</span>, sǎo mù).</strong> This is the defining activity of Qingming. Families travel to ancestral graves, often in rural areas, to clean and maintain the burial sites. The ritual involves pulling weeds, sweeping away debris, washing headstones, and repainting inscriptions if faded. Fresh soil may be added to the mound. The physical act of cleaning is itself a form of respect &mdash; it demonstrates that the dead are not forgotten.</p>
  <p><strong>Offering food and drink.</strong> Families place food offerings at the grave: typically fruit, cooked dishes, rice, wine or tea, and the deceased's favourite foods when known. The food is arranged before the headstone as if setting a table for a guest. After the ritual, the family consumes the food together at the graveside &mdash; a shared meal that bridges the living and the dead.</p>
  <p><strong>Burning incense and paper offerings.</strong> Incense sticks are lit and placed before the grave. Joss paper (<span class="chinese-char">紙錢</span>, zhǐ qián, literally "paper money") and spirit money are burned in the belief that the fire transforms the offerings into goods usable in the spirit world. Traditional items include paper ingots, paper clothing, and paper houses. Modern additions sometimes include paper smartphones, paper cars, or paper designer goods &mdash; though these contemporary items are debated by traditionalists.</p>
  <p><strong>Bowing and prayer.</strong> Family members bow three times before the grave (the number three holds ritual significance in Chinese culture) and may address the ancestors directly, sharing family news, asking for blessings, or simply expressing that they are remembered.</p>
  <p><strong>Spring outing (<span class="chinese-char">踏青</span>, tàqīng).</strong> Qingming coincides with the most beautiful period of spring in much of China. After the solemn ritual of tomb sweeping, families often enjoy a countryside walk or picnic. The <em>tàqīng</em> tradition is documented as early as the Sui Dynasty (581&ndash;618) and reflects the Chinese view that honouring the dead and celebrating the living are complementary, not contradictory.</p>
  <p><strong>Flying kites.</strong> Kite flying is a traditional Qingming activity, particularly for children. In some regions, kites are flown at night with small lanterns attached to the strings, creating lines of light across the sky. Cutting the kite string and letting the kite fly away is sometimes practised as a symbolic release of bad luck or illness.</p>
  <p><strong>Wearing willow branches.</strong> Willow branches are inserted into the ground near graves and sometimes worn in the hair or placed above doorways. The willow is one of the first trees to bud in spring, symbolising renewal and vitality. A folk saying states: <em>"If you do not wear willow on Qingming, you will become a yellow dog in the next life"</em> &mdash; a humorous warning that underscores the custom's deep cultural embeddedness.</p>
</section>
</div>

<div class="lang-tc">
<section id="traditions">
  <h2>傳統習俗</h2>
  <p>清明習俗歷經數百年傳承，核心傳統始終如一：</p>
  <p><strong>掃墓（<span class="chinese-char">掃墓</span>，sǎo mù）。</strong>這是清明節最核心的活動。家人前往祖墳——通常在鄉村地區——清掃和維護墓地。儀式包括拔除雜草、清掃垃圾、擦洗墓碑，若碑文褪色則重新描漆。墓丘上可能會添加新土。掃墓這一行為本身就是一種敬意的表達——它表明逝者未被遺忘。</p>
  <p><strong>供奉食物和飲品。</strong>家人在墓前擺放祭品：通常包括水果、熟食、米飯、酒或茶，以及先人生前喜愛的食物。食物在墓碑前整齊擺放，彷彿為賓客設席。儀式結束後，全家人在墓前一同享用祭食——這頓共餐連接著生者與逝者。</p>
  <p><strong>焚香和燒紙。</strong>在墓前點燃香燭。紙錢（<span class="chinese-char">紙錢</span>，zhǐ qián）和冥幣在火中焚燒，人們相信火焰能將祭品轉化為陰間可用之物。傳統祭品包括紙元寶、紙衣服和紙房子。現代新增的祭品有時包括紙手機、紙汽車或紙名牌商品——但這些當代祭品引發了傳統主義者的爭議。</p>
  <p><strong>跪拜和祈禱。</strong>家人在墓前鞠躬三次（三在中國文化中具有儀式意義），並可能直接對祖先說話，分享家庭近況、祈求庇佑，或僅僅表達對先人的懷念。</p>
  <p><strong>踏青（<span class="chinese-char">踏青</span>，tàqīng）。</strong>清明時節正值中國大部分地區春光最美之時。在莊嚴的掃墓儀式之後，家人常常享受一次郊外散步或野餐。踏青傳統最早見於隋代（581-618年）的記載，體現了中國人的觀念：追念逝者與享受生活是相輔相成的，而非相互矛盾。</p>
  <p><strong>放風箏。</strong>放風箏是清明的傳統活動，尤其受兒童喜愛。在部分地區，人們在夜間放風箏，風箏線上繫著小燈籠，在夜空中形成一道道光線。有時人們會剪斷風箏線，讓風箏飛走，象徵著放走厄運或疾病。</p>
  <p><strong>佩戴柳枝。</strong>柳枝被插在墳墓旁的泥土中，有時佩戴在頭上或掛在門楣之上。柳樹是春天最早發芽的樹木之一，象徵著新生與活力。民間有句俗語：<em>「清明不戴柳，來世變黃狗」</em>——這句幽默的警語折射出這一習俗在文化中根深蒂固的地位。</p>
</section>
</div>

<div class="lang-sc">
<section id="traditions">
  <h2>传统习俗</h2>
  <p>清明习俗历经数百年传承，核心传统始终如一：</p>
  <p><strong>扫墓（<span class="chinese-char">掃墓</span>，sǎo mù）。</strong>这是清明节最核心的活动。家人前往祖坟——通常在乡村地区——清扫和维护墓地。仪式包括拔除杂草、清扫垃圾、擦洗墓碑，若碑文褪色则重新描漆。墓丘上可能会添加新土。扫墓这一行为本身就是一种敬意的表达——它表明逝者未被遗忘。</p>
  <p><strong>供奉食物和饮品。</strong>家人在墓前摆放祭品：通常包括水果、熟食、米饭、酒或茶，以及先人生前喜爱的食物。食物在墓碑前整齐摆放，仿佛为宾客设席。仪式结束后，全家人在墓前一同享用祭食——这顿共餐连接着生者与逝者。</p>
  <p><strong>焚香和烧纸。</strong>在墓前点燃香烛。纸钱（<span class="chinese-char">紙錢</span>，zhǐ qián）和冥币在火中焚烧，人们相信火焰能将祭品转化为阴间可用之物。传统祭品包括纸元宝、纸衣服和纸房子。现代新增的祭品有时包括纸手机、纸汽车或纸名牌商品——但这些当代祭品引发了传统主义者的争议。</p>
  <p><strong>跪拜和祈祷。</strong>家人在墓前鞠躬三次（三在中国文化中具有仪式意义），并可能直接对祖先说话，分享家庭近况、祈求庇佑，或仅仅表达对先人的怀念。</p>
  <p><strong>踏青（<span class="chinese-char">踏青</span>，tàqīng）。</strong>清明时节正值中国大部分地区春光最美之时。在庄严的扫墓仪式之后，家人常常享受一次郊外散步或野餐。踏青传统最早见于隋代（581-618年）的记载，体现了中国人的观念：追念逝者与享受生活是相辅相成的，而非相互矛盾。</p>
  <p><strong>放风筝。</strong>放风筝是清明的传统活动，尤其受儿童喜爱。在部分地区，人们在夜间放风筝，风筝线上系着小灯笼，在夜空中形成一道道光线。有时人们会剪断风筝线，让风筝飞走，象征着放走厄运或疾病。</p>
  <p><strong>佩戴柳枝。</strong>柳枝被插在坟墓旁的泥土中，有时佩戴在头上或挂在门楣之上。柳树是春天最早发芽的树木之一，象征着新生与活力。民间有句俗语：<em>"清明不戴柳，来世变黄狗"</em>——这句幽默的警语折射出这一习俗在文化中根深蒂固的地位。</p>
</section>
</div>

<div class="lang-en">
<section id="cold-food">
  <h2>The Cold Food Festival Connection</h2>
  <p>The Cold Food Festival (<span class="chinese-char">寒食節</span>, Hánshí Jié) originally fell one or two days before Qingming and required that all fires be extinguished and only cold food be eaten for up to three days. The festival commemorates Jie Zitui's loyalty and the duke's remorse, but its roots may be even older &mdash; some scholars connect it to an ancient spring fire-renewal rite documented in the <em>Zuo Zhuan</em> (<span class="chinese-char">左傳</span>), where old fires were extinguished and new fires kindled to mark the transition of seasons.</p>
  <p>By the Song Dynasty (960&ndash;1279), the Cold Food Festival and Qingming had effectively merged. The <em>Dongjing Meng Hua Lu</em> (<span class="chinese-char">東京夢華錄</span>), a detailed account of life in the Northern Song capital Kaifeng, describes the combined festival period as lasting several days and encompassing tomb sweeping, cold food, spring outings, and official court ceremonies.</p>
  <p>Traditional cold food dishes associated with Qingming include:</p>
  <table class="elements-table">
    <thead><tr><th>Dish</th><th>Chinese Name</th><th>Region</th><th>Description</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Qingtuan</td><td><span class="chinese-char">青糰</span></td><td>Jiangnan (Shanghai, Zhejiang)</td><td>Green glutinous rice balls made with mugwort or barley grass juice, filled with sweet red bean paste</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Runbing</td><td><span class="chinese-char">潤餅</span></td><td>Fujian, Taiwan</td><td>Thin spring roll wrappers filled with mixed vegetables, peanut powder, and sometimes meat</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Zitui Mo</td><td><span class="chinese-char">子推饃</span></td><td>Shanxi</td><td>Steamed bread shaped into animals or flowers, named after Jie Zitui</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Eggs dyed with herbs</td><td><span class="chinese-char">染色蛋</span></td><td>Various regions</td><td>Hard-boiled eggs coloured with wormwood, willow, or other spring plants</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
</section>
</div>

<div class="lang-tc">
<section id="cold-food">
  <h2>寒食節的淵源</h2>
  <p>寒食節（<span class="chinese-char">寒食節</span>，Hánshí Jié）最初在清明前一兩天，要求熄滅所有火源，連續三天只食冷食。寒食節紀念介子推的忠義和晉文公的悔恨，但其根源可能更為古老——有學者將其與《左傳》（<span class="chinese-char">左傳</span>）記載的古代春季換火儀式聯繫起來，舊火熄滅、新火點燃，以此標誌季節的更替。</p>
  <p>到宋代（960-1279年），寒食節和清明節已實質合併。《東京夢華錄》（<span class="chinese-char">東京夢華錄</span>）詳細記述了北宋都城開封的生活，描述合併後的節日持續數天，涵蓋掃墓、冷食、踏青和宮廷典禮。</p>
  <p>與清明相關的傳統冷食包括：</p>
